Overall, it just feels like you're over exaggerating his weakness.

Throughout the eras, Felynes and Humans have had a rather symbiotic relationship. Providing food and protection for one another in the face of the great beasts that roam the land. No such interaction is more of a pinnacle of that relationship than that of a Hunter and one of its Felyne companions. In exchange for shelter and share of the spoils, a Felyne will battle along side a hunter providing health aide, and assistance in critical moments. Relationships between Hunters and Felynes that hunt together for a long time can grow quite strong, sometimes even intimate. While Romantic relations between the two races are frowned upon, a Hunters special status generally causes the populace to largely ignore such indulgence. While such trysts are usually brief, merely the result of blood running high from a good hunt, some Hunters and Felynes choose to mate for life, instead of eventually moving on to one of their own species. ("No one can know them better than the one they hunt with, train with, live with and love with. So why find a lesser mate?") Is often the philosophy of such couplings. It is still long debated amongst hunters of which species makes for a better wife/husband even today.

Part 2:

The one thing that really stuck out for me was your sentence structure. I'm not sure if it's a facet of the type of writing you do in your day job or whether English is your second language*, but you tend to write in the passive voice (Subject is acted upon by the predicate, as opposed to the subject acting on the predicate). While still grammatically correct, it makes for some rather interesting phrasing. It tends to muddy the waters a bit when using prepositions to build out your thoughts. I say this as someone who has the same problem, I.E. too many adjective / adverb phrases.

Additionally, you do tend to repeat words in places where its not necessary. While less noticeable in some places, the scene leading up to Dave's capture, his first encounter with Anna, and the scene in AI with Dave's mom really stuck out in my mind. The bad news is that I don't have a systematic approach to improve this issue. The good news is that you can get a feel for it by reading more novels.

My best advice for this would be threefold:
1.) When writing, keep the subject as the actor (as opposed to what or who is being acted upon).
2.) Don't be afraid to shorten up your sentences. Believe it or not, fleshing out an idea in two sentences can flow better than a single long sentence.
3.) Read some of the better known, action heavy, novels from authors like Michael Crichton or Dan Brown. They'll help you develop an 'ear' for writing that flows.

*If it is your second language, I'm impressed as. I only bring it up because your heavier focus on time and tense has a more eastern feel, as opposed to the more western/English object focus.

Link to some info on passive vs. active voice: https://writing.wisc.edu/Handbook/CCS_activevoice.html

Again, decent writing over all, just try to come up for air every now and again to read something else and keep your 'sound' a bit more natural.
